<subSubSection id="945CE403D12FE3AC73E64CBAFDC2FA49" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="A185B1D96785E99A803D9B3EFA08CF7E" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CC7E595F329C7C30D6E0E657F0481D07" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">
From the Spanish word Cayapa, with reference to the Chachi indigenous group that inhabits a great portion of the evergreen lowland forests of the Equatorial 
<normalizedToken id="497DF67F5AF0923C727F875A06491D10" originalValue="Chocó">Choco</normalizedToken>
in Ecuador. The word Chachi means 
<normalizedToken id="F2A7042699FA6C320EB02764373F086E" originalValue="‘pure’">'pure'</normalizedToken>
in the 
<normalizedToken id="239C9AFF0D3B3FD86C3A1E14EE4B89CD" originalValue="Cha’palaachi">Cha'palaachi</normalizedToken>
language. The species name was first proposed by the late Ecuadorian botanist J. Jaramillo as a written annotation on herbarium specimens, but was never validly published.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="372A651AE7BF552AC7100497ED4C712B" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" type="conservation status">
<paragraph id="F609C70601B20919F286DB782ABBED8C" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="009D1C50BE2DBD252F6817E5ED2F21EB" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">
<taxonomicName id="57B008FF6FCB7E40A56047EF7366B74E" authorityName="J. Jaram. &amp; J. E. Guevara" authorityYear="2020" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Elaeocarpaceae" genus="Sloanea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Sloanea cayapensis" order="Oxalidales" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cayapensis">
<emphasis id="84E9342A3823F64A80A5E28F8ED08148" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Sloanea cayapensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be catalogued as Endangered (EN) following 
<bibRefCitation id="684C9365CEE259BA9A6F10E7AE6CABFA" author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="Brittonia" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" refId="B8" refString="IUCN, 2012. IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1. Second edition. Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, [iv +] 32 pp." title="IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1. Second edition. Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, [iv +] 32 pp." year="2012">IUCN (2012)</bibRefCitation>
criterion A2c, which indicates: &quot;An observed, estimated, inferred or suspected population size reduction of ≥ 50% over the last 10 years or three generations, whichever is the longer, where the reduction or its causes may not have ceased or may not be understood or may not be reversible&quot; and criterion B1ab(iii), which indicates: &quot;Extent of occurrence (EOO) estimated to be less than 5,000 km2 and estimates indicating continuing decline, observed, inferred or projected, in area, extent and/or quality of habitat&quot;. The analysis using the GeoCat tool for geospatial conservation assessment determined an EOO of 2000 km2 (
<bibRefCitation id="957FDF4240A4A7B7C319A72AD2AE645B" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.150.2109" author="Bachman, S" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" pagination="117 - 126" refId="B1" refString="Bachman, S, Moat, J, Hill, AW, de Torre, J, Scott, B, 2011. Supporting Red List threat assessments with GeoCAT: Geospatial conservation assessment tool. ZooKeys 150: 117 - 126, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.150.2109" title="Supporting Red List threat assessments with GeoCAT: Geospatial conservation assessment tool." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.150.2109" volume="150" year="2011">Bachman et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="B6AEEA8139AF77302C13CB3870961154" authorityName="J. Jaram. &amp; J. E. Guevara" authorityYear="2020" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Elaeocarpaceae" genus="Sloanea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Sloanea cayapensis" order="Oxalidales" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cayapensis">
<emphasis id="3AA2B8FCCF9F389543703B600C63075C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Sloanea cayapensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known from two localities on the banks of the Cayapas River, in the lowland evergreen forest of the Equatorial 
<normalizedToken id="B80AA121E46E3048B1BD040D7A7AB2E6" originalValue="Chocó">Choco</normalizedToken>
. The area has suffered extensive clear-cutting in the last 30 years, leading to a drastic reduction of native forests and expansion of oil palm plantations and illegal logging, these being the major threats faced by the species. Since collection of the types in 2003, no other specimens of this species have been recorded despite the fact that subsequent field trips have sampled the same habitat occupied by this species. Over the last 26 years, the annual rate of deforestation in the lowland evergreen forest of the Equatorial 
<normalizedToken id="B9983DF62AC83CB65791BCF46BE64FE0" originalValue="Chocó">Choco</normalizedToken>
in Ecuador has been 1.7-2.9% and the remnant forests in this area cover just 24% of their original extent (
<bibRefCitation id="1AF3A5E9EA1CF05CADEC7F7E1AB299B7" author="Sierra, R" journalOrPublisher="dh Books, England" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" refId="B16" refString="Sierra, R, 2013. Patrones y factores de deforestacion en el Ecuador continental, 1990-2010. Y un acercamiento a los proximos 10 anos. Conservacion Internacional Ecuador y Forest Trends. Quito." title="Patrones y factores de deforestacion en el Ecuador continental, 1990 - 2010. Y un acercamiento a los proximos 10 anos. Conservacion Internacional Ecuador y Forest Trends. Quito." year="2013">Sierra 2013</bibRefCitation>
). Consequently, the habitat occupied by this species in Ecuador has been drastically reduced. However, the species is likely to occur in similar habitats in the Colombian 
<normalizedToken id="7BDD6C24A8BA82CEE5E18B3CCDCF589F" originalValue="Chocó">Choco</normalizedToken>
where the dynamic of deforestation is less drastic but a cause for concern.
</paragraph>
